<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-constructing-tangents" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Constructing Tangents</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Construct a tangent to a circle at a given point
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To lead learners to discover that a tangent to a circle is perpendicular to the radius at the point of tangency.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate as learners draw and measure. Prompt any group that gets an angle far from 90° to check whether their line is truly tangent (touching at exactly one point, neither cutting through nor missing the circle). After groups share results, confirm that the answer is always 90° and ask learners why they think this must be so.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="activity-tangent-discovery">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            In pairs, draw a circle of any size and mark its centre <m>O</m>. Then mark any point <m>P</m> on the circumference.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw the radius <m>OP</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Try to draw a straight line through <m>P</m> that <em>just touches</em> the circle at <m>P</m> — it should not cut through the circle, and it should not miss the circle entirely. This type of line is called a <term>tangent</term> to the circle at <m>P</m>.
                        </p>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Learners may find this tricky at first. Encourage them to hold a ruler at <m>P</m> and rotate it slowly until only one point on the ruler's edge touches the circle. Accept any line that is approximately correct.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use a protractor to measure the angle between your tangent line and the radius <m>OP</m> at the point <m>P</m>. Write down your measurement.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare your measurement with other groups. What do you notice? Why do you think this is the case?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                All groups should measure approximately <m>90°</m>. The tangent is perpendicular to the radius at the point of tangency. This is the key property that makes the compass-and-straightedge construction possible: to construct a tangent at <m>P</m>, we need to construct a line through <m>P</m> that is perpendicular to the radius <m>OP</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To formalise the tangent-radius property and teach the compass-and-straightedge construction.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Confirm the result from the activity: at the point of tangency, the tangent is perpendicular to the radius. Write this as the key property on the board.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Walk through the six construction steps using the diagrams below, pausing at each step for learners to follow along on their own paper with compass and straightedge.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    After completing the construction, ask learners to verify that their tangent line is perpendicular to the radius using a set square or protractor.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A <term>tangent</term> to a circle is a straight line that touches the circle at exactly one point, called the <term>point of tangency</term>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        At the point of tangency, the tangent is <em>perpendicular to the radius</em>. Conversely, any line through a point on the circle that is perpendicular to the radius at that point is the tangent at that point.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        From any point outside a circle, exactly two tangents can be drawn to the circle. The distances from the external point to the two points of tangency are <em>equal</em>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Constructing a Tangent at a Point on a Circle</title>
        <p>
            To construct a tangent to a circle at a point <m>P</m> on the circle, using only a pair of compasses and a straightedge, follow these steps.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw a circle with centre <m>O</m> and mark the point <m>P</m> on the circle.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-step-1">
                        <caption>Step 1: Circle with centre <m>O</m> and point <m>P</m> on the circumference.</caption>
                        <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,0){P}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(O,P)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](O)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](P)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw the radius <m>OP</m> and extend the line beyond <m>P</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-step-2">
                        <caption>Step 2: Radius <m>OP</m> extended beyond <m>P</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="55%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,0){P}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(4.7,0){Ext}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                                    \tkzDrawSegment(O,Ext)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(O,P)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](O)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](P)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Set your compasses to the length <m>OP</m>. Placing the compass point at <m>P</m>, mark a point <m>Q</m> on the extended line on the far side of <m>P</m> from <m>O</m>, so that <m>PQ = OP</m>. The point <m>P</m> is now the midpoint of <m>OQ</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-step-3">
                        <caption>Step 3: Point <m>Q</m> marked so that <m>PQ = OP</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="58%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,0){P}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(4,0){Q}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments(O,P P,Q)
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,P P,Q)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(O,P,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](O)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](P,Q)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Open your compasses to a width greater than half of <m>OQ</m>. With the compass point at <m>O</m>, draw arcs above and below the line <m>OQ</m>. Without changing the compass width, place the compass point at <m>Q</m> and draw arcs above and below the line, crossing the first arcs. Label the two crossing points <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-step-4">
                        <caption>Step 4: Compass arcs from <m>O</m> and from <m>Q</m>, crossing at <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="58%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,0){P}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(4,0){Q}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,1.5){X}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,-1.5){Y}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments(O,P P,Q)
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,P P,Q)
                                    \draw[dashed,gray] (1.607,-1.915) arc[start angle=-50, end angle=50, radius=2.5];
                                    \draw[dashed,gray] (2.393,1.915) arc[start angle=130, end angle=230, radius=2.5];
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(O,P,Q,X,Y)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](O)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](P,Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](X)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Y)
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw the straight line through <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>. This is the <term>tangent</term> to the circle at <m>P</m>.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-step-5">
                        <caption>Step 5: Line through <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> drawn, passing through <m>P</m> at a right angle to <m>OP</m>.</caption>
                        <image width="58%">
                            <latex-image>
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,0){P}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(4,0){Q}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,1.5){X}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,-1.5){Y}
                                    \tkzDefPoint(2,2.3){Xtop}
                                    \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                                    \tkzDrawSegments(O,P P,Q)
                                    \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,P P,Q)
                                    \draw[dashed,gray] (1.607,-1.915) arc[start angle=-50, end angle=50, radius=2.5];
                                    \draw[dashed,gray] (2.393,1.915) arc[start angle=130, end angle=230, radius=2.5];
                                    \draw[blue,thick] (2,-2.3) -- (2,2.3);
                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](O,P,Xtop)
                                    \tkzDrawPoints(O,P,Q,X,Y)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below left](O)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below right](P)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[below](Q)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](X)
                                    \tkzLabelPoints[right](Y)
                                    \node[blue] at (2.9,2.2) {\small tangent};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Why does this work?</em> Since <m>P</m> is the midpoint of <m>OQ</m>, the perpendicular bisector of <m>OQ</m> passes through <m>P</m> and is perpendicular to <m>OQ</m>. Since <m>OP</m> is a radius and the constructed line is perpendicular to <m>OP</m> at <m>P</m>, it is exactly the tangent to the circle at <m>P</m>.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example xml:id="example-tangent-construction-worked">
        <title>Constructing a Tangent</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The diagram shows a circle with centre <m>O</m> and a point <m>P</m> at the top of the circle. Describe the steps to construct the tangent to the circle at <m>P</m>, and show the completed construction.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-eg1-given">
                <caption>Circle with centre <m>O</m> and point <m>P</m> at the top of the circle.</caption>
                <image width="40%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,2){P}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(O,P)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](O)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="1.">
                    <li><p>Draw the radius <m>OP</m> and extend it beyond <m>P</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Set compasses to length <m>OP</m>. With centre <m>P</m>, mark point <m>Q</m> on the extension above <m>P</m> so that <m>PQ = OP</m>. Now <m>P</m> is the midpoint of <m>OQ</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Open compasses to more than half the length of <m>OQ</m>. Draw arcs from <m>O</m> and from <m>Q</m> to either side of the line <m>OQ</m>, and label the crossing points <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Draw the straight line through <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>. This line passes through <m>P</m> and is the tangent at <m>P</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                The completed construction is shown below. Because <m>P</m> is at the top of the circle, the radius <m>OP</m> is vertical, and so the tangent is horizontal.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-eg1-solution">
                <caption>Completed tangent construction. The blue horizontal line is the tangent at <m>P</m>.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,2){P}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,4){Q}
                            \tkzDefPoint(-1.5,2){X}
                            \tkzDefPoint(1.5,2){Y}
                            \tkzDefPoint(2.5,2){Tang}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(O,P P,Q)
                            \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,P P,Q)
                            \draw[dashed,gray] (1.915,1.607) arc[start angle=40, end angle=140, radius=2.5];
                            \draw[dashed,gray] (-1.915,2.393) arc[start angle=220, end angle=320, radius=2.5];
                            \draw[blue,very thick] (-2.5,2) -- (2.5,2);
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.2](O,P,Tang)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(O,P,Q,X,Y)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](O)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above](Q, X, Y)
                            \node[blue] at (2.9,1.7) {\small tangent};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-identifying-tangents">
        <title>Identifying a Tangent</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The diagram shows a circle with centre <m>O</m> and three lines labelled <m>\ell_1</m>, <m>\ell_2</m>, and <m>\ell_3</m>. Identify which line is a tangent to the circle and explain how you can tell.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-identify-tangent-eg">
                <caption>Circle with three lines.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(2,0){P}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(O)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](O)
                            \draw[thick] (2,-3) -- (2,3);
                            \draw[thick] (-3,0.8) -- (3,0.8);
                            \draw[thick] (3.5,-3) -- (3.5,3);
                            \node at (2.45,2.8) {$\ell_1$};
                            \node at (3.25,0.7) {$\ell_2$};
                            \node at (3.95,2.8) {$\ell_3$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The line <m>\ell_1</m> is the tangent. It touches the circle at exactly one point (the rightmost point of the circle) and does not enter the interior of the circle.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\ell_2</m> is a <term>secant</term>: it crosses the circle at two distinct points, so it is not a tangent.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\ell_3</m> does not touch the circle at all, so it is neither a tangent nor a secant.
            </p>
            <p>
                We can confirm that <m>\ell_1</m> is the tangent because it is perpendicular to the radius drawn to its point of contact.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-equal-tangent-lengths">
        <title>Equal Tangent Lengths</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Two tangents are drawn from an external point <m>T</m> to a circle with centre <m>O</m> and radius <m>2</m> cm. The tangents touch the circle at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. Given that <m>OT = 5</m> cm, find the length of each tangent.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-equal-tangents-eg">
                <caption>Two tangents from external point <m>T</m>.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                            \tkzDefPoint(2,0){Pr}
                            \tkzDefPoint(5,0){T}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0.8,1.833){A}
                            \tkzDefPoint(0.8,-1.833){B}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](O,Pr)
                            \tkzDrawSegments(T,A T,B)
                            \tkzDrawSegments[dashed](O,A O,B O,T)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](O,A,T)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.15](O,B,T)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(O,T,A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below left](O)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[right](T)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[above right](A)
                            \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since <m>OA</m> is a radius and <m>TA</m> is a tangent at <m>A</m>, we have <m>\angle OAT = 90°</m>. By Pythagoras' theorem in triangle <m>OAT</m>:
                <md>
                    TA^2 = OT^2 - OA^2 = 5^2 - 2^2 = 25 - 4 = 21.
                </md>
                So <m>TA = \sqrt{21} \approx 4.58</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                By the same argument in triangle <m>OBT</m>, <m>TB = \sqrt{21}</m> cm. The two tangent lengths are equal, confirming the property stated in the Key Ideas above.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="exercise-identify-tangent-lines">
            <title>Identifying Tangent Lines</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The diagram shows a circle with centre <m>O</m> and four lines labelled (a), (b), (c), and (d). For each line, state whether it is a tangent, a secant, a diameter, or misses the circle entirely, and justify your answer.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-identify-four-lines">
                    <caption>Circle with four lines.</caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){O}
                                \tkzDefPoint(2,0){P}
                                \tkzDefPoint(-1.2, 1.6){A}
                                \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,P)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(O)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](O)
                                \tkzDefLine[tangent at=A](O)
                                \tkzGetPoint{h}
                                \tkzDrawLine[add = 4 and 3](A,h)
                                \tkzLabelLine[pos=1.25,right](A,h){(c)}
                                \draw[thick] (2,-3.2) -- (2,3.2);
                                \draw[thick] (-3,0.7) -- (3,0.7);
                                \draw[thick] (3.5,-3.2) -- (3.5,3.2);
                                \draw[thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
                                \node at (2.45,3.0) {\small (a)};
                                \node at (3.3,0.7) {\small (b)};
                                \node at (3.3,0) {\small (d)};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>(a) is the <em>tangent</em> — it touches the circle at exactly one point (the rightmost point).</p></li>
                        <li><p>(b) is a <em>secant</em> — it cuts through the circle at two points.</p></li>
                        <li><p>(c) <em>misses the circle entirely</em> — it is further from the centre than the radius.</p></li>
                        <li><p>(d) is a <em>diameter</em> — it passes through the centre <m>O</m> and intersects the circle at two diametrically opposite points.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-construct-tangent-at-point">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw a circle of radius 4 cm with centre <m>O</m>. Mark any point <m>P</m> on the circumference. Using a pair of compasses and a straightedge only, construct the tangent to the circle at <m>P</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Check your construction by measuring the angle between your tangent and the radius <m>OP</m> with a protractor.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-construct-external-tangents">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw a circle with centre <m>O</m> and radius 3 cm. Mark an external point <m>T</m> such that <m>OT = 6</m> cm. Construct both tangents from <m>T</m> to the circle and label the points of tangency <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Calculate the exact length of each tangent.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    By Pythagoras' theorem in triangle <m>OAT</m> (where <m>\angle OAT = 90°</m>):
                    <md>
                        TA^2 = OT^2 - OA^2 = 6^2 - 3^2 = 36 - 9 = 27.
                    </md>
                    So <m>TA = \sqrt{27} = 3\sqrt{3} \approx 5.2</m> cm, and by symmetry <m>TB = 3\sqrt{3}</m> cm.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-equal-tangents-discovery">
            <title>Equal Tangents from an External Point</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw a circle with centre <m>O</m> and mark an external point <m>T</m>. Construct both tangents from <m>T</m> to the circle and label the points of tangency <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>Measure <m>TA</m> and <m>TB</m>. What do you notice?</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Explain why this must always be true. (<em>Hint:</em> consider triangles <m>OAT</m> and <m>OBT</m>. What can you say about their sides and angles?)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p><m>TA = TB</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                In triangles <m>OAT</m> and <m>OBT</m>:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><p><m>OA = OB</m> (both radii of the same circle),</p></li>
                                    <li><p><m>OT = OT</m> (common side),</p></li>
                                    <li><p><m>\angle OAT = \angle OBT = 90°</m> (radius perpendicular to tangent at point of tangency).</p></li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                By the RHS congruence rule, <m>\triangle OAT \equiv \triangle OBT</m>, and therefore <m>TA = TB</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-tangent-uniqueness">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Can two different tangent lines to a circle be drawn at the same point on the circle? Explain your answer.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    No. At any point <m>P</m> on the circle, the tangent must be perpendicular to the radius <m>OP</m>. There is exactly one line through <m>P</m> perpendicular to <m>OP</m>, so there is exactly one tangent at <m>P</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-two-touching-circles">
            <title>Two Touching Circles</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The diagram shows two circles with centres <m>O_1</m> and <m>O_2</m> and radii <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> that touch at a single point <m>T</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-two-touching-circles">
                    <caption>Two circles touching at point <m>T</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \tkzDefPoint(-1,0){O1}
                                \tkzDefPoint(2,0){O2}
                                \tkzDefPoint(0,0){T}
                                \tkzDrawCircle(O1,T)
                                \tkzDrawCircle(O2,T)
                                \draw[dashed] (-2.3,0) -- (4.3,0);
                                \tkzDrawPoints(O1,O2,T)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below](O1,O2)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](T)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using a ruler, draw a tangent to each circle at <m>T</m>. What do you notice about the two tangents?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The tangent at <m>T</m> is perpendicular to the radius of each circle at <m>T</m>. What does this tell you about the two radii <m>O_1T</m> and <m>O_2T</m>? What does this mean for the positions of <m>O_1</m>, <m>T</m>, and <m>O_2</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write down the distance <m>O_1O_2</m> in terms of <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The two tangents are the same line. There is only one tangent to a circle at any given point, and at <m>T</m> both circles share this unique common tangent.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Both radii <m>O_1T</m> and <m>O_2T</m> must be perpendicular to the same tangent line at <m>T</m>. Since two lines through the same point that are both perpendicular to the same line must be the same line, <m>O_1T</m> and <m>O_2T</m> are collinear. Therefore <m>O_1</m>, <m>T</m>, and <m>O_2</m> all lie on the same straight line.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>O_1</m>, <m>T</m>, <m>O_2</m> are collinear and <m>T</m> lies between the two centres (the circles are externally tangent),
                                <md>
                                    O_1O_2 = r_1 + r_2.
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

